 And so now we just want to have a little discussion

68
00:02:25,320 --> 00:02:27,660
 where we get a chance to share the hope and love of Christ

69
00:02:27,660 --> 00:02:29,740
 over any political system with our friends.

70
00:02:29,740 --> 00:02:30,980
 And so we're in this conversation.

71
00:02:30,980 --> 00:02:32,700
 And if one thing happened in that conversation,

72
00:02:32,700 --> 00:02:34,620
 that's the reason I start with this story.

73
00:02:34,620 --> 00:02:36,660
 There was a girl who interrupted the conversation

74
00:02:36,660 --> 00:02:39,700
 pretty angrily, accused me of anger,

75
00:02:39,700 --> 00:02:43,040
 but in her anger, in her angry accusation,

76
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:44,420
 she asked me a question.

77
00:02:44,420 --> 00:02:46,420
 It was like a moment came where she was going to put down

78
00:02:46,420 --> 00:02:48,980
 her anger and she was going to be polite.

79
00:02:48,980 --> 00:02:50,980
 And like the manners like kicked in.

80
00:02:50,980 --> 00:02:53,140
 And when that happened, she chose a sentence

81
00:02:53,140 --> 00:02:56,820
 that no one has ever said to me before out of manners.

82
00:02:56,820 --> 00:02:59,260
 She said this sentence and I'm being totally serious.

83
00:02:59,260 --> 00:03:00,460
 She was totally sincere.

84
00:03:00,460 --> 00:03:01,420
 She didn't say it for a laugh.

85
00:03:01,420 --> 00:03:03,260
 She didn't do anything out of the ordinary.

86
00:03:03,260 --> 00:03:04,100
 She was being kind.

87
00:03:04,100 --> 00:03:08,960
 She said, "Do you identify as a white male?"

88
00:03:08,960 --> 00:03:11,060
 That's what she said.

89
00:03:11,060 --> 00:03:13,020
 And it wasn't like, you know,

90
00:03:13,020 --> 00:03:14,940
 that's not how we introduce ourselves in Fort Worth, okay?

91
00:03:14,940 --> 00:03:16,540
 And so I'm like, if you do,

92
00:03:16,540 --> 00:03:17,780
 then you would be considered rude

93
00:03:17,780 --> 00:03:18,820
 or you'd be making fun of somebody

94
00:03:18,820 --> 00:03:20,020
 or maybe making a bad joke.

95
00:03:20,020 --> 00:03:21,380
 And like, ooh, that's kind of insensitive.

96
00:03:21,380 --> 00:03:23,140
 And so it would just be misunderstood.

97
00:03:23,140 --> 00:03:27,020
 But she was being completely sincere,

98
00:03:27,020 --> 00:03:28,940
 totally kindhearted even.

99
00:03:28,940 --> 00:03:31,860
 This was her way of showing love and care and acceptance

100
00:03:31,860 --> 00:03:33,720
 was just to ask me, do I identify as a white male?

101
00:03:33,720 --> 00:03:35,980
 Which she politely also asked the guy

102
00:03:35,980 --> 00:03:37,420
 that we were talking to.

103
00:03:37,420 --> 00:03:39,700
 And so he answered yes, I answered yes.

104
00:03:39,700 --> 00:03:40,580
 And the conversation went on.

105
00:03:40,580 --> 00:03:43,040
 We did get a chance to share with them explicitly

106
00:03:43,040 --> 00:03:44,780
 the hope and faith that we have in Christ.

107
00:03:44,780 --> 00:03:46,340
 And both groups kind of parted high-fiving

108
00:03:46,340 --> 00:03:47,660
 because they got to talk about what they wanted

109
00:03:47,660 --> 00:03:48,800
 to talk about, which was politics.

110
00:03:48,800 --> 00:03:50,460
 And we got to talk about what we wanted to talk about,

111
00:03:50,460 --> 00:03:51,300
 which was Christ.

112
00:03:51,300 --> 00:03:52,120
 And so everybody left happy.

113
00:03:52,120 --> 00:03:55,180
 But there was that one sentence that stuck with me.

114
00:03:55,180 --> 00:03:56,700
 And I realized she was so sincere.

115
00:03:56,700 --> 00:03:59,300
 If I had told her, like, I feel five-five

116
00:03:59,300 --> 00:04:00,900
 instead of six feet tall, she would have been,

117
00:04:00,900 --> 00:04:01,740
 she'd be like, okay.

118
00:04:01,740 --> 00:04:03,060
 She probably would have started looking right here.

119
00:04:03,060 --> 00:04:05,900
 I mean, she was going to totally buy in.

120
00:04:05,900 --> 00:04:07,620
 And so if I had told her that I was Asian,

121
00:04:07,620 --> 00:04:10,020
 she would have totally played by those rules.

122
00:04:10,020 --> 00:04:11,500
 If I had told her I felt like a woman,

123
00:04:11,500 --> 00:04:13,860
 she would have called me ma'am out of respect,

124
00:04:13,860 --> 00:04:15,300
 like not even to be funny.

125
00:04:15,300 --> 00:04:16,500
 This is not a game to her.

126
00:04:16,500 --> 00:04:19,040
 She is so serious and so sincere.

127
00:04:19,040 --> 00:04:24,040
 And I realized this is not just a protester

128
00:04:24,040 --> 00:04:25,760
 versus pastor conversation.

129
00:04:25,760 --> 00:04:27,520
 This is an every person conversation.

130
00:04:27,520 --> 00:04:30,980
 This is a me, personally conversation.

131
00:04:30,980 --> 00:04:34,240
 Because what she said was, she used the word identify.

132
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:37,880
 But she could have used the word feel interchangeably.

133
00:04:37,880 --> 00:04:39,800
 And so for her, catch this, don't miss this,

134
00:04:39,800 --> 00:04:42,840
 or you'll miss us from the start if you miss this.

135
00:04:42,840 --> 00:04:47,840
 She was saying that your feelings are your identity.

136
00:04:47,840 --> 00:04:52,840
 The way you feel is who you are.

137
00:04:52,840 --> 00:04:53,940
 So if you want to find out who you are,

138
00:04:53,940 --> 00:04:55,900
 just look inside yourself, find where your feelings are,

139
00:04:55,900 --> 00:04:58,760
 follow your feelings, and we'll just call that your identity.

140
00:04:58,760 --> 00:05:01,040
 Your feelings decide your identity.

141
00:05:01,040 --> 00:05:02,520
 She had wholeheartedly bought into that,

142
00:05:02,520 --> 00:05:04,420
 and she was going to extend me the same privilege.

143
00:05:04,420 --> 00:05:07,460
 And so she was fully convinced that to commit,

144
00:05:07,460 --> 00:05:09,180
 or rather to commit to your feelings,

145
00:05:09,180 --> 00:05:12,060
 is to find your identity.

146
00:05:12,060 --> 00:05:13,140
 That's where she was.

147
00:05:13,140 --> 00:05:16,660
 And I realized, man, this is not just something

148
00:05:16,660 --> 00:05:18,020
 I should shake my head at.

149
00:05:18,020 --> 00:05:19,340
 And this conversation this evening

150
00:05:19,340 --> 00:05:20,940
 is not about what's going on in society

151
00:05:20,940 --> 00:05:22,060
 in some other part of the country.

152
00:05:22,060 --> 00:05:25,100
 I realized this is a me conversation.

153
00:05:25,100 --> 00:05:26,820
 Because there has been a time in my life,

154
00:05:26,820 --> 00:05:29,220
 and I realize much more often than I think,

155
00:05:29,220 --> 00:05:33,020
 that my feelings and my identity actually don't agree.

156
00:05:33,020 --> 00:05:35,880
 Not about gender, not necessarily about race.

157
00:05:35,880 --> 00:05:37,640
 But I think back to the time I became a Christian.

158
00:05:37,640 --> 00:05:39,180
 See, before I was a believer in Christ,

159
00:05:39,180 --> 00:05:40,740
 before I was a follower of Jesus,

160
00:05:40,740 --> 00:05:41,860
 I did whatever I felt like.

161
00:05:41,860 --> 00:05:43,420
 If I felt like having sex, that's what I would do.

162
00:05:43,420 --> 00:05:44,700
 If I felt like looking at pornography,

163
00:05:44,700 --> 00:05:45,620
 that's what I would do.

164
00:05:45,620 --> 00:05:47,420
 If I felt like running from the police,

165
00:05:47,420 --> 00:05:49,620
 that's what I would do, and did, twice.

166
00:05:49,620 --> 00:05:52,500
 Dad, I've never actually told you that, but that happened.

167
00:05:52,500 --> 00:05:53,340
 And so,

168
00:05:53,340 --> 00:05:58,660
 so whenever you are following a feeling,

169
00:05:58,660 --> 00:06:00,280
 before you're a Christ follower, that's just who you are.

170
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:02,260
 So my feelings and my identity were exactly the same.

171
00:06:02,260 --> 00:06:04,440
 I was the guy who did what I felt like.

172
00:06:04,440 --> 00:06:05,920
 Feelings and identity were exactly the same.

173
00:06:05,920 --> 00:06:09,220
 But then I became a Christian, in a moment.

174
00:06:09,220 --> 00:06:11,460
 And my identity changed.

175
00:06:11,460 --> 00:06:13,220
 Now, you heard David talk about that a little bit last week

176
00:06:13,220 --> 00:06:14,580
 in Amnesia Part One.

177
00:06:14,580 --> 00:06:17,220
 The old was gone and the new had come.

178
00:06:17,220 --> 00:06:19,660
 And so my identity changed in a split second.

179
00:06:19,660 --> 00:06:23,140
 What happened to my feelings was exactly nothing.

180
00:06:23,140 --> 00:06:26,980
 I still felt like doing everything that I had done before.

181
00:06:26,980 --> 00:06:30,060
 I was now a Christian who had an identity in Christ.

182
00:06:30,060 --> 00:06:31,900
 I'd been given this brand new identity, slate clean,

183
00:06:31,900 --> 00:06:34,660
 but the only problem was I still felt like looking at porn,

184
00:06:34,660 --> 00:06:36,540
 having sex, running from the police,

185
00:06:36,540 --> 00:06:38,060
 and just generally partying.

186
00:06:38,060 --> 00:06:40,140
 And I was about to go to college.

187
00:06:40,140 --> 00:06:43,820
 But this identity versus feelings clash.

188
00:06:43,820 --> 00:06:45,620
 And so the question for us all tonight

189
00:06:45,620 --> 00:06:48,220
 is not whether feelings are powerful.

190
00:06:48,220 --> 00:06:49,480
 Can we agree feelings are powerful?

191
00:06:49,480 --> 00:06:53,480
 Hurts, pains, doubts, wants, desires, hopes, dreams,

192
00:06:53,480 --> 00:06:56,100
 all these are incredibly powerful.

193
00:06:56,100 --> 00:06:58,340
 Families start because somebody gets a feeling.

194
00:06:58,340 --> 00:06:59,820
 Actually, because two people get a feeling.

195
00:06:59,820 --> 00:07:00,660
 That's why you're here.

196
00:07:00,660 --> 00:07:02,060
 Two people got a feeling.

197
00:07:02,060 --> 00:07:06,460
 So feelings are powerful things.

198
00:07:06,460 --> 00:07:09,500
 Families break apart because somebody gets a feeling.

199
00:07:10,460 --> 00:07:12,420
 Some of you move cities because you got a feeling.

200
00:07:12,420 --> 00:07:14,100
 Some of you are here right now for some reason

201
00:07:14,100 --> 00:07:16,660
 that you just decided that you had a feeling

202
00:07:16,660 --> 00:07:17,740
 you should come.

203
00:07:17,740 --> 00:07:20,780
 Feelings are incredibly powerful things.

204
00:07:20,780 --> 00:07:23,580
 The question is, the question for tonight is,

205
00:07:23,580 --> 00:07:26,780
 which one should we commit to?

206
00:07:26,780 --> 00:07:28,320
 Should we, as my friend from Boulder

207
00:07:28,320 --> 00:07:30,180
 would politely encourage me,

208
00:07:30,180 --> 00:07:32,380
 should we commit to our feelings and say,

209
00:07:32,380 --> 00:07:33,780
 you know what, that's gonna be who I am.

210
00:07:33,780 --> 00:07:35,900
 I'm gonna be the person who does what I feel like.

211
00:07:35,900 --> 00:07:38,540
 When I do what I feel like, I'll find out who I am.

212
00:07:38,540 --> 00:07:40,940
 Or should we, what if I told you

213
00:07:40,940 --> 00:07:43,940
 that finding your identity

214
00:07:43,940 --> 00:07:48,060
 was not a matter of following your feelings,

215
00:07:48,060 --> 00:07:51,300
 but it was actually a matter of resisting them,

216
00:07:51,300 --> 00:07:53,700
 sometimes for a long time,

217
00:07:53,700 --> 00:07:56,700
 sometimes with much difficulty.

218
00:07:56,700 --> 00:07:59,520
 And you don't have to tell me that feelings are difficult.

219
00:07:59,520 --> 00:08:02,280
 I have had addictions.

220
00:08:02,280 --> 00:08:03,120
 I get it.

221
00:08:03,120 --> 00:08:05,420
 Feelings are powerful.

222
00:08:05,420 --> 00:08:06,540
 And I know some of you, even tonight,

223
00:08:06,540 --> 00:08:07,880
 you're here and you've got a feeling

224
00:08:07,880 --> 00:08:09,240
 that you wish you didn't have.

225
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:11,100
 You're like, I wish this feeling wasn't here.

226
00:08:11,100 --> 00:08:12,940
 In fact, I've asked God to take it away.

227
00:08:12,940 --> 00:08:14,420
 I wish that I didn't feel this way.

228
00:08:14,420 --> 00:08:15,540
 And here you are, you're at the porch,

229
00:08:15,540 --> 00:08:17,020
 and you're like, maybe the momentum of the porch,

230
00:08:17,020 --> 00:08:19,060
 maybe somebody can sing it out or preach it out.

231
00:08:19,060 --> 00:08:20,180
 We'll just porch it out.

232
00:08:20,180 --> 00:08:22,900
 Like for some reason, you think this feeling could go away

233
00:08:22,900 --> 00:08:25,020
 and you're sitting there hopeful, hopeful, hopeful

234
00:08:25,020 --> 00:08:27,780
 that a feeling would disappear.

235
00:08:27,780 --> 00:08:29,780
 And there it is.

236
00:08:29,780 --> 00:08:32,220
 That's the power of a feeling.

237
00:08:32,220 --> 00:08:34,040
 So we can all agree that feelings are powerful.

238
00:08:34,040 --> 00:08:36,820
 And we can agree that feelings and identity

239
00:08:36,820 --> 00:08:37,880
 can sometimes clash.

240
00:08:37,880 --> 00:08:39,440
 That's just common human experience.

241
00:08:39,440 --> 00:08:42,340
 The question for tonight is, which is a little less clear,

242
00:08:42,340 --> 00:08:44,620
 which one should we commit to?

243
00:08:44,620 --> 00:08:46,220
 Should we commit to our feelings and say,

244
00:08:46,220 --> 00:08:48,240
 that's who we'll be, or should we commit to who we'll be?

245
00:08:48,240 --> 00:08:53,240
 And then sometimes, with much pain, filter our feelings.

246
00:08:53,240 --> 00:08:55,140
 That's the question for tonight.

247
00:08:55,140 --> 00:08:57,180
 And so what I wanna do tonight is I'd love to introduce you

248
00:08:57,180 --> 00:09:00,340
 to a man in the Bible that you might not have met before.

249
00:09:00,340 --> 00:09:03,740
 He is in Genesis chapter 25, and his name is Esau.

250
00:09:03,740 --> 00:09:06,700
 Esau is a man with a big identity from God,

251
00:09:06,700 --> 00:09:08,460
 a huge identity from God, in fact,

252
00:09:08,460 --> 00:09:10,880
 much greater than he even knew at the time.

253
00:09:10,880 --> 00:09:12,440
 But the man with the big identity

254
00:09:12,440 --> 00:09:13,740
 got a little feeling one day.

255
00:09:13,740 --> 00:09:15,620
 And so I wanna show you as best I can

256
00:09:15,620 --> 00:09:19,460
 from Genesis chapter 25, the way feelings and identity

257
00:09:19,460 --> 00:09:21,660
 interact and which ones we should embrace

258
00:09:21,660 --> 00:09:24,580
 and which one we should be prepared to resist.

259
00:09:24,580 --> 00:09:27,060
 Now Esau, I said Esau was given an identity from God.

